1. Plot the data and comment on its features. What can you observe? To what political , economical or social event/s it can be linked?

global_economy |>
  filter(Country == "Russian Federation") |> 
  autoplot(Population / 1e6) +
  labs(title = "Population (millions) in Russian Federation ")

The data is annual so we cannot observe seasonality, nor there seem to be any cyclical behaviours, which make sense given that the kind of data we are examining.

In 1960 the population was approximately 120 million, the slope of the increase changes in 1970, but remains steady reaching the peak around 1991, which is the of the collapse of the Soviet Union, officially ending in the 25th of December of that year.The Russian Federation taking power the next day. It followed the lifting of the price control policy which had been in place for decades, therefore prices were now determined by the market forces. This lead to economic downturn of the country for the following decade, the now unregulated market made the prices for basic good and services rapidly increase. This of course led to inflation and worsened living standard for the Russian population. The worsening of the economic condition will impact population growth under Malthus economic theory. Historically, it is not the most appropriate economic growth theory that we should refer to, but the it does not deny the principle. So from that peak year population decreases,reaching its minimum level in around 2010.In 2020 the population was of around 144 million people, which is still lower that the early 90s.

2. Fit a linear trend model and compare this to a piecewise linear trend model with knots at 1993 and 2008.

ts_Russia<- global_economy %>%
  filter(Country == "Russian Federation") %>%
  select(Population)%>%
  index_by(Year)

# linear trend model
fit_lm<- ts_Russia %>%
  model(TSLM(Population ~ trend())) # we do not add seasonality

augment(fit_lm)%>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Year)) +
  geom_line(aes(y = Population, colour = "Data")) +
  geom_line(aes(y = .fitted, colour = "Fitted")) +
  scale_colour_manual(
    values = c(Data = "black", Fitted = "purple")
  ) 

#Piecewise regression model
fit_kn<- ts_Russia %>%
  model(piecewise= TSLM(Population ~ trend(knots=c(1993,2008)))) 

augment(fit_kn)%>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Year)) +
  geom_line(aes(y = Population, colour = "Data")) +
  geom_line(aes(y = .fitted, colour = "Fitted")) +
  scale_colour_manual(
    values = c(Data = "black", Fitted = "red")
  )

Comparison

The two models do have linear regression assumptions, but we need to take note that where the model changes slope, the structure of the error might change as well. For the linear regression model we assume that the errors in the model: - have mean zero and are homoskedastic (have constant variance, so to generate prediction intervals); - they are not autocorrelated (nor correlated to the selected predictor variables), so the past errors hold no information about the future ones; - they are normally distributed, meaning they are symmetric

We check assumptions for the linear model:

augment(fit_lm) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = .fitted / 1e6, y = Population / 1e6 )) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(
    y = "Actual Values",
    x = "Fitted Values",
    title = "Fitted Versus Observed"
  ) + geom_abline(intercept = 0, slope = 1)

The linear model does not fit the data well, given that the observations show clear pattern, this was predictable.

We computed the sample mean to compare it with the Standard error which is the size of the error that the model produces on average.

The linear regression model does not seem to be a good fit, the errors are not independent (autocorrelation is still present) nor normally distributed (the histogram is not symmetric). We cannot assume that the resdiuals are stationary nor reduced to white noise from fitting a linear regression.

3. Generate forecasts from these two models for the five years after the end of the data, and comment on the results.

Given we are regression only on trend(), generating an ex-post forecast is not an option.

#Forecast for the linear model
fc_lm<- fit_lm %>% fabletools::forecast(h=10)

ts_Russia %>%
  autoplot(Population) +
  geom_line(data = fitted(fit_lm),
            aes(y = .fitted, colour = .model)) +
  autolayer(fc_lm) 

#Forecast for the piecewise model
fc_kn<- fit_kn %>% fabletools::forecast(h=10)

ts_Russia %>%
  autoplot(Population) +
  geom_line(data = fitted(fit_kn),
            aes(y = .fitted, colour = .model)) +
  autolayer(fc_kn)

Because of the better fit of the second model, the confidence interval is smaller for the second fitted function prediction.

Another option could be to regress Population on other economic indicators, which for historical reasons have a lot of missing data, but we know might have actually influenced the evolution of the population in the country.

ts_Russia2<- global_economy %>%
  filter(Country == "Russian Federation") %>%
  select(Population, Growth, CPI)%>%
  index_by(Year)

fit_lm2<- ts_Russia2 %>%

The data all in all shows constant growth over the decades, in the most recent decade the level has stabilised a lot. This can be easily attributed to the change of life styles after the 2008 and 2011-2012 crises. In 1960 the population level was around 30 million people, around the start of the 80s the inclination of the evolution of the level slowed down.In the 80s and 90s Spain implemented policies intended to increase immigration which definitely impacted the population level. The slope changes becoming more steep at the start of the new century. Again, if available population average age would be a good indicator that we could consult.

Fitting the two models:

ts_Spain<- global_economy %>%
  filter(Country == "Spain") %>%
  select(Population)%>%
  index_by(Year)

fit_lm_sp<- ts_Spain %>%
  model(TSLM(Population ~ trend())) # we do not add seasonality

augment(fit_lm_sp)%>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Year)) +
  geom_line(aes(y = Population, colour = "Data")) +
  geom_line(aes(y = .fitted, colour = "Fitted")) +
  scale_colour_manual(
    values = c(Data = "black", Fitted = "green")
  ) 

fit_kn_sp<- ts_Spain %>%
  model(piecewise= TSLM(Population ~ trend(knots=c(1980,2001,2010)))) 

augment(fit_kn_sp)%>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Year)) +
  geom_line(aes(y = Population, colour = "Data")) +
  geom_line(aes(y = .fitted, colour = "Fitted")) +
  scale_colour_manual(
    values = c(Data = "black", Fitted = "blue")
  )

The knots are placed so that the fitted function follws the data more closely.

The R^2 is higher than the one displayed by the former model. Autocorrelation is much lower, there is some in lag 1 and lag 2, meaning that the error of the estimated data-point corresponding to the year y is correlated with the error of the two previous years. TH residuals appear more centred around 0, but definitely no symmetric. The residuals appear more random in the scatter plot but not so much. Adding more knots might be a recommended.

Forecast

fc_lm_sp<- fit_lm_sp %>% fabletools::forecast(h=10)

ts_Spain %>%
  autoplot(Population) +

            aes(y = .fitted, colour = .model)) +

fc_kn_sp<- fit_kn_sp %>% fabletools::forecast(h=10)

ts_Spain %>%
  autoplot(Population) +
  geom_line(data = fitted(fit_kn_sp),
            aes(y = .fitted, colour = .model)) +
  autolayer(fc_kn_sp)

Here as well the piecewise regression has smaller intervals around the point forecast, less uncertainty on the beta parameter.The prediction has Students t distribution. The prediction interval is \([x*\hat{b}\pm t_{T-(p+1);1-a/2}s\sqrt{(1+x*(X^T X)^{-1}x*^T)}]\). The amplitude of the CIs can be inflated by the term \(sx*(X^T X)^{-1}x*^T\) which as mentioned above is the uncertainty on the coefficient. As the number of observations (\(T\)) grows the t distribution will converge to normal and the term will move towards 0.
